<EssayLayout
  title="Shor + post-quantum"
  subtitle="Grover gives a quadratic speedup on unstructured search; Shor gives an exponential speedup on factoring. The engine that powers Shor is the quantum Fourier transform — a unitary that turns periodic structure into sharp spikes. This essay teaches the QFT, probes the classical period-finding lesson it exploits, then assembles the full N=15 Shor circuit and frames the post-quantum cryptography migration it forces."
  description="See how the quantum Fourier transform converts periodic amplitude patterns into measurement spikes, probe the multiplicative-order structure Shor's period-finding subroutine exploits, then inspect the full 8-qubit N=15 Shor circuit (static, copy-as-Qiskit) and the RSA → NIST post-quantum-standard migration it threatens. Covers ALG-05/06/07 and USE-04."
>
  <p class="text-sm italic text-ink-subtle">
    New to quantum computing? Start at <a href="/qubit">/qubit</a>
    and walk forward — every concept used here (Dirac notation, the
    Hadamard gate, the QFT) is introduced in the earlier essays.
  </p>

  <p>
    The <a href="/grover">previous essay</a> closed with a sharp line:
    Grover does <em>not</em> break RSA — that's Shor. RSA's hard
    problem is integer factoring, and unstructured search gives you
    no leverage on factoring. Shor's algorithm goes after a different
    structure entirely: <em>periodicity</em>. If you can find the
    period <code>r</code> of the function
    <code>f(x) = a<sup>x</sup> mod N</code>, classical number theory
    gives you a non-trivial factor of <code>N</code> with constant
    probability. The whole quantum machinery — superposition, the
    QFT, measurement — is in service of finding that one number.
  </p>

  <p>
    This essay teaches the QFT first, the period-finding intuition
    second, then assembles them into the full <code>N = 15</code>
    Shor circuit and frames the post-quantum cryptography migration
    it forces. The QFT is the engine; period finding is the
    problem the engine solves; RSA is what shipping that engine at
    scale threatens; NIST's four standardized post-quantum
    primitives are what the migration is migrating to.
  </p>

  <h2>The quantum Fourier transform turns periods into spikes</h2>

  <p>
    The QFT is the quantum analog of the discrete Fourier transform.
    It's a single <em>unitary</em> (a reversible quantum operation)
    <code>F</code> acting on an <code>n</code>-qubit register; it
    maps the computational basis state <code>|x⟩</code> to a uniform
    superposition with phase
    <code>e<sup>2πi·xk/N</sup></code> on each <code>|k⟩</code>, where
    <code>N = 2<sup>n</sup></code>. The mechanical detail isn't the
    lesson. The lesson is what happens to amplitudes:
  </p>

  <MathBlock tex="F\,|x\rangle \;=\; \frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} e^{2\pi i\, xk / N} |k\rangle" />

  <p>
    Apply <code>F</code> to a single basis state and you get a uniform
    probability distribution over the output — every bin has weight
    <code>1/N</code>. Apply it to a <em>uniform</em> superposition of
    every basis state and the output concentrates on
    <code>|0⟩</code>. Apply it to a state that has periodic
    structure — say, equal weight on
    <code>{0, 4, 8, 12}</code> over a 4-qubit register — and the
    output is no longer uniform. It's a comb: spikes at evenly
    spaced bins, and zero in between. That's the only fact the rest
    of Shor's algorithm needs.
  </p>

  <p>
    The widget below runs a real 4-qubit QFT on five preset input
    states plus a custom mode. The "period-4 comb" preset is the one
    to dwell on: an input concentrated on every fourth basis state
    produces an output concentrated on every fourth output bin
    (<code>|0000⟩, |0100⟩, |1000⟩, |1100⟩</code>). The frequency 4
    in the input shows up as a stride of <code>16/4 = 4</code> in
    the output.
  </p>

  <QFTVisualizer
    caption="4-qubit QFT (N = 16). Top chart is input probabilities; bottom chart is output probabilities after F. Try the period-4 comb preset to see the canonical 'spacing in = spacing out' pattern Shor relies on. Custom mode reveals a 16-amplitude editor for ad-hoc experiments."
  />

  <h2>Period finding: a^x mod N is periodic</h2>

  <p>
    Pick any <code>a</code> coprime to <code>N</code> and look at the
    sequence <code>a<sup>0</sup>, a<sup>1</sup>, a<sup>2</sup>, …
    (mod N)</code>. For <code>a = 7, N = 15</code> you get
    <code>1, 7, 4, 13, 1, 7, 4, 13, …</code>: a cycle of length
    four. That cycle length is the <strong>multiplicative
    order</strong> of <code>a</code> modulo <code>N</code>, and it's
    the <code>r</code> Shor's algorithm hunts.
  </p>

  <p>
    Classically, you can compute <code>r</code> by just walking the
    sequence — that's exactly what the widget below does. For small
    <code>N</code> it's instant. The catch is that for
    cryptographically interesting <code>N</code> (two large primes
    multiplied), <code>r</code> can be astronomically large and the
    walk is intractable. Shor's algorithm replaces the walk with a
    quantum register: superpose every <code>x</code>, evaluate
    <code>a<sup>x</sup> mod N</code> in superposition, then apply
    the QFT. The output probability distribution peaks at multiples
    of <code>Q/r</code> (where <code>Q = 2<sup>n</sup></code>) —
    exactly the comb pattern you saw above. Measuring it gives you a
    bin near a multiple of <code>Q/r</code>; the
    <em>continued-fractions algorithm</em> (a classical number-theory
    trick that reconstructs a clean fraction from a noisy decimal)
    turns that into <code>r</code>; classical post-processing turns
    <code>r</code> into a factor of <code>N</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Probe the classical side directly:
  </p>

  <PeriodFinding
    caption="Probe a^x mod N for N ≤ 15. The widget computes the multiplicative order r classically, shows the cycle, and lists where a 4-qubit QFT would peak (at j·16/r for j = 0…r−1) if you fed this function into Shor's quantum subroutine."
  />

  <h2>The full N = 15 Shor circuit</h2>

  <p>
    Putting both halves together — a register that holds every
    <code>x</code> in superposition while a second register computes
    <code>a<sup>x</sup> mod N</code>, followed by an inverse QFT on
    the first register — gives you the textbook Shor circuit. The
    smallest non-trivial instance is <code>N = 15</code> with
    <code>a = 7</code>: a 4-qubit counting register, a 4-qubit work
    register, controlled modular-exponentiation blocks, an inverse
    QFT on the counting register, and four measurements that yield a
    bin near a multiple of <code>16/r</code> with <code>r = 4</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Eight qubits is twice the sandbox cap. The simulator on this site
    is hard-capped at 4 qubits — extending it for N=15 would force a
    weaker UX everywhere and still wouldn't approach
    cryptographically interesting <code>N</code>. So the N=15 circuit
    here is a <strong>static artifact</strong>, not a runnable
    sandbox fragment. You built the engine in the QFT and
    period-finding widgets above; the diagram below is the engine
    bolted into the full car. Copy it as Qiskit and run it on real
    hardware to see it actually factor 15.
  </p>

  <LargeCircuitView circuit={shor15} />

  <p>
    The four logical blocks read left-to-right:
  </p>

  <ul class="my-4 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      <strong>Init</strong>: Hadamards on the counting register
      <code>q0..q3</code> put it into the uniform superposition over
      <code>x = 0..15</code>. The work register stays in
      <code>|0001⟩</code> (representing the integer 1, so the modular
      exponentiation starts from <code>7<sup>0</sup> mod 15 = 1</code>).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Modular exponentiation</strong>: four controlled blocks
      that apply
      <code>×7<sup>1</sup>, ×7<sup>2</sup>, ×7<sup>4</sup>, ×7<sup>8</sup>
      mod 15</code> to the work register, gated on the respective
      counting qubit. Together they multiply the work register by
      <code>7<sup>x</sup> mod 15</code> for whatever value
      <code>x</code> the counting register is in superposition over —
      this is the function whose period we're trying to find.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Inverse QFT</strong>: the comb-builder from the
      previous section, run in reverse on the counting register.
      Under the hood it's the standard textbook decomposition —
      Hadamards, a ladder of controlled phase shifts, and two SWAPs
      to flip the register order — but you can read it as a single
      block that turns periodic amplitude patterns into measurement
      spikes.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Measure</strong>: four measurements on the counting
      register. Classical post-processing (the same continued-fractions
      trick from earlier) maps the measured integer back to a
      candidate period; the comments in the exported Qiskit show
      exactly that.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Why "Copy as Qiskit"? Because the honest deliverable here is
    portability, not in-browser execution. The exported Python uses
    Qiskit's <code>QFT(4).inverse()</code> for the IQFT and a
    documented stub for <code>c_amod15</code> — the only piece you
    need to fill in before running it on
    <code>AerSimulator</code> or real IBM hardware.
  </p>

  <h2>What that engine threatens: RSA</h2>

  <p>
    Shor's algorithm factors integers in polynomial time on a
    quantum computer. RSA's security rests on the assumption that
    factoring is hard. Stitch those two facts together and you get
    the post-quantum cryptography conversation: <em>given enough
    fault-tolerant logical qubits</em>, today's RSA keys are
    breakable. The widget below frames how big "enough" is.
  </p>

  <RSACountdown />

  <p>
    Two things to take away from playing with that slider:
  </p>

  <ul class="my-4 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      The textbook estimate <code>2·k + overhead</code> is for
      <strong>logical</strong> qubits — error-corrected qubits whose
      effective error rate is low enough to run a full Shor
      circuit. The <em>physical</em>-qubit cost under surface-code
      error correction is one to two orders of magnitude larger
      (see Gidney &amp; Ekerå 2021 linked under the widget).
    </li>
    <li>
      The gap between "today" and "break RSA-2048" is enormous.
      That gap is the entire reason the post-quantum
      standardization work happened on a multi-year timeline — not
      because anyone is breaking RSA tomorrow, but because the
      migration itself takes years.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What developers should do today: NIST's four PQC standards</h2>

  <p>
    NIST finalized the first three post-quantum standards in 2024
    (FIPS 203, 204, 205) and is moving on a fourth (FN-DSA / Falcon)
    as a draft. The cards below summarize each one with a link to
    the official publication — don't take any website's word for it,
    read the standard yourself.
  </p>

  <PQCCards />

  <p>
    The practical answer to "does this site break RSA?" is the same
    as in the <a href="/grover">Grover</a> essay: no. The accurate
    answer is more interesting — the math underneath the threat
    lives in the widgets you just used, the migration window is
    measured in years of engineering effort, and the four
    algorithms above are what the migration is migrating
    <em>to</em>.
  </p>

  <h2>Self-test</h2>

  <ol class="my-6 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      In the QFTVisualizer, set the input to a single basis state
      (any of the <code>|xxxx⟩</code> presets). What's the output
      probability distribution? Why does the QFT of a single basis
      state always have uniform <em>magnitude</em>? (Hint: look at
      the formula above — the phase rotates but the magnitude
      <code>|1/√N|</code> is constant.)
    </li>
    <li>
      In the period-finding widget, set <code>N = 15, a = 4</code>.
      Why does the sequence collapse so quickly? Where would a
      4-qubit QFT peak if you ran this function through Shor?
    </li>
    <li>
      The period-finding widget refuses <code>a</code> values that
      aren't coprime with <code>N</code>. Why is that a precondition
      of Shor's algorithm — what would go wrong in the quantum
      subroutine if <code>gcd(a, N) ≠ 1</code>? (Hint: think about
      what <code>a<sup>x</sup> mod N</code> looks like when it shares
      a factor with <code>N</code>.)
    </li>
  </ol>

  <MathNerds title="Why the QFT peaks at multiples of Q/r">
    <p>
      Let <code>r</code> be the period of
      <code>f(x) = a<sup>x</sup> mod N</code> and let
      <code>Q = 2<sup>n</sup></code> be the register size. Suppose
      <code>r</code> divides <code>Q</code> evenly. Prepare the
      quantum register in the uniform superposition over the indices
      where <code>f</code> hits some value <code>y</code>:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="|\psi_y\rangle \;=\; \sqrt{\frac{r}{Q}}\,\sum_{j=0}^{Q/r - 1}\, |x_0 + j r\rangle" />
    <p>
      where <code>x_0</code> is the smallest <code>x</code> with
      <code>f(x_0) = y</code>. Apply the QFT:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="F|\psi_y\rangle \;=\; \frac{1}{\sqrt{r}}\,\sum_{j=0}^{r-1}\, e^{2\pi i\, x_0\, j Q/(r Q)} \, |jQ/r\rangle" />
    <p>
      Every output amplitude away from a multiple of
      <code>Q/r</code> cancels — a geometric series in
      <code>e<sup>2πi/r</sup></code> sums to zero unless its phase is
      stationary. The surviving amplitudes sit at <code>k = jQ/r</code>
      for <code>j = 0, 1, …, r−1</code>, each with probability
      <code>1/r</code>. That's the comb pattern the period-4 preset
      paints in QFTVisualizer.
    </p>
    <p>
      When <code>r</code> does <em>not</em> divide <code>Q</code> the
      peaks blur into nearby bins, but they still concentrate near
      the same <code>jQ/r</code> values; the continued-fractions
      algorithm recovers <code>r</code> from a measured bin with
      high probability. The peak-hint panel in PeriodFinding shows
      the rounded predictions when divisibility fails.
    </p>
  </MathNerds>

